full_text:
@Alphadogstudio1 @richey_paula When C.S. Lewis talked about writing for children, he identified 3 methods.

1. Trying to churn out what the market wants.
2. Writing for a specific child.
3. Writing because you have something to say that fits that format.

He identified Tolkien's work as 2 and his own as 3.

2) Do you know everything you need after the first fight.

b"@cirsova Chrono Trigger is rich. But you don't have to appreciate the richness to get into it, or even to complete it.

When I say JRPG-Lite, my main criteria are twofold:
1) Is it less than 30 hours.
2) Do you know everything you need after the first fight."

full_text:
@cirsova My design concerns between the JRPGs and TTRPGs would be wildly different.

E.g. I intend to give health in clumps of 4, represented as quarter-hearts in my JRPGs. In a TTRPG I wouldn't do that because fractions are an elegant mechanic as a picture, but clunky as paperwork.

@AStratelates Deep into that darkness, peering
Long I stood there, wond'ring, fearing,

Ever dared to dream before.

And the darkness gave no token
And the only word there spoken
Was the whispered word, "Lenore?"

I'm happy I get to publicly take that stance. I'm not happy that the consequence is I may need to tighten by belt.

full_text:
Key to this is honest recognition of my priorities.

I want to make cash money off my work so I can live comfortably in yonder swamp.

But I also want to exorcise these characters and stories from my head, and get them into the hands of any who might find them amusing.

If I've an obligation not to murder you, you've a resulting right not to be murdered by me.

full_text(utf-8):
b"@RedHedgedragon @HabitualLevity @AscendantComics @Fiannawolf2 Balancing this is very much a reader expectation thing.

A pulp reader might want you to tell the emotional bits and show the action. A romance reader would rather you tell the action and show the emotions.

It's more nuanced than that, but there's the general idea."

@RedHedgedragon @HabitualLevity @AscendantComics @Fiannawolf2 It's a slider. You can say "Bob was mad." You can say, "Bob scowled furiously and punched the brick wall." You can take several positions between. "Bob punched the all angrily."

Recognizing that slider and fine-tuning it to the needs of the story is a strength of prose.

@RedHedgedragon @HabitualLevity @AscendantComics @Fiannawolf2 So you have a character Bob, and he is mad.

In film or comics, you want Bob to make an angry face, probably punch or kick something. Not just have a narrator say "Bob was mad."

Show don't tell.

In text, though...

full_text:
@HabitualLevity @RedHedgedragon @AscendantComics @Fiannawolf2 Show; Don't Tell is filmwriting and comic writing advice that got transplanted to books. It's not %100 bad, but in writing showing and telling are a spectrum rather than a binary, and you can tell things you could never show.

Thus, SDT as dogma undercuts the strengths of prose.
full_text(utf-8): b"@HabitualLevity @RedHedgedragon @AscendantComics @Fiannawolf2 Show; Don't Tell is filmwriting and comic writing advice that got transplanted to books. Religious freedom works as a treaty. I won't kill you if you won't kill me. I'll let you worship if you won't try to seize the reigns of power.

Notably, treaties do not apply to non-signatories or violators.

full_text:
Religious freedom is based on the Peace of Westphalia, which is based on the Peace of Augsburg.

In both instances, factions of Christianity are signing treaties saying they will stop executing each other as heretics, and in return they won't overthrow each other's governments.

full_text:
I don't support absolute religious freedom.

Aztecs should not be permitted to rip out human hearts to try and ensure the rain, for instance.

So, if religious freedom is not an absolute, how do we decide which faiths are permitted?

The answer is found in the idea's history: https://t.co/KhV7jzuc8j

b"@AHelleneAuthor 7/7

And I was standing outside my door praying the Lord's Prayer while pulling on my pants.

Curiously, despite remaining on the meds for more than a decade after, the experiences stopped when I left college."

b"@AHelleneAuthor 6/n

Later, at a secular college, when I fancied myself a schoolteacher, I awoke to a giant skeletal arm feeling around my dorm room like a cat's paw feeling under a door.

Again, reality shifted as though a switch had been flipped."

b'@AHelleneAuthor 5/n

This was at a nondenom Christian college. I was a weird choir boy, so my wandering around singing was taken in a stride.

I have no knowledge of exorcism to this day, or whether my song was any good, or where it came from.'

full_text:
@AHelleneAuthor 4/n

In college, I saw things.

I saw a procession of black-robed phantoms marching into a fellow student, like she was a door. I stood, mesmerized.

Then, like a light switch had been flipped, there were no phantoms, and I was singing an exorcism.
full_text(utf-8):
b'@AHelleneAuthor 4/n

I saw a procession of black-robed phantoms marching into a fellow student, like she was a door. I stood, mesmerized.

full_text:
@AHelleneAuthor 3/n

Even now, I can't be sure, as I was under the influence of mind altering medications at the time.
full_text(utf-8): b"@AHelleneAuthor 3/n\n\nEven now, I can't be sure, as I was under the influence of mind altering medications at the time."

b"@AHelleneAuthor 2/n

A symptom of bipolar is religious hallucinations. Seeing angels or demons is not uncommon.

As I believed in both the supernatural AND that I had a disorder that produced hallucinations of the supernatural, I'd no way of knowing whether what I saw was real or a brain glitch."

full_text:
@AHelleneAuthor 1/n

Context: When I was a kid I was diagnosed with depression and put on meds.

When I was in college, the diagnosis was changed to bipolar, and the meds changed.

A couple years ago, I found out it was all a hilarious misunderstanding. The symptoms were caused by the pills.

full_text: @DJSchreffler It's something worth working out in a lot more detail, and I commend Lewis's The Abolition of Man and Tolkien's On Fairy Stories to whomever would essay the attempt, but alas, I haven't the time just now.
full_text(utf-8): b"@DJSchreffler It's something worth working out in a lot more detail, and I commend Lewis's The Abolition of Man and Tolkien's On Fairy Stories to whomever would essay the attempt, but alas, I haven't the time just now."

b'@DJSchreffler That said, man was made as king. We are meant, to a degree, to subdue the world.

Mastery of the world may be the sorcery of Sauron, but it may be the kingship of Aragorn. But it must be mastery in submission to the Tao.

So, my brief sketch is too simple.'

full_text:
@DJSchreffler My theory here is that there are two outlooks: the religious outlook, where you are conformed to the Tao, and the sorceror's outlook, where you conform the world to you.

Fantasy ought align with the first; sci-fi the second. But most fantasy these days is, in spirit, sci fi.
full_text(utf-8): b"@DJSchreffler My theory here is that there are two outlooks: the religious outlook, where you are conformed to the Tao, and the sorceror's outlook, where you conform the world to you.\n\nFantasy ought align with the first; sci-fi the second.
